  "business_context": "Constituent records reflect a deliberate modeling choice in nonprofit CRMs: rather than splitting Person (Contact) from Organization (Account) the way B2B CRMs do, treat both as variants of a single Constituent entity with a Type discriminator (Individual / Organization). The argument for this approach is that nonprofits track giving from both individuals and organizations using the same fundraising workflows and reporting — the differences are smaller than B2B sales relationships (where the Person and Organization roles are more distinct). Bloomerang is the strongest example of this pattern — its primary entity is Constituent, with Type=Individual or Type=Organization gating which attributes apply (FirstName/LastName for Individual; FullName for Organization). CiviCRM partially follows this pattern (Contact entity with subtypes Individual / Household / Organization) but retains a somewhat richer per-subtype structure. Salesforce NPSP, EspoCRM, and the B2B systems keep Contact and Account separate and don't have a Constituent entity. The presence of this catalog entry is mostly documentary — it captures the unified-entity pattern so V2 understands it when ingesting client modeling, and so cross-system mapping can translate cleanly between unified and split models. When interviewing clients on a Bloomerang or CiviCRM deployment, \"Constituent\" maps to the catalog entries Contact, Account, and Household combined; on NPSP/Salesforce/EspoCRM it doesn't exist as such.",
